"The Fountain of Youth at St. Augustine. This is near where Ponce de Leon, discoverer of Florida, first landed, is this legendary spring, the waters of which were supposed to restore the lost charm and vigor of youth. (State Archives of Florida)",

"The Fountain of Youth in Saint Augustine, Florida. The spring is said to have been visited in 1513 by Ponce de Leon. It is believed to have been enclosed in 1565 when the first permanent settlement in the United States was established at Saint Augustine, Florida. Property purchased by Dr. Luella Day McConnell in 1901 who began to charge an admission price to drink from the waters of the free flowing spring found on the estate. (State Archives of Florida)",
"The Ponce de Leon statue at the entrance to the spring in De Leon Springs, Florida. (State Archives of Florida/Johnson)",
"A woman sitting on the Fountain of Youth attraction in Saint Augustine, Florida. (State Archives of Florida)",

"The Fountain of Youth in St. Augustine, Florida .According to tradition it is the exact spot where Juan de Leon, the Spanish explorer in search of the Fountain of Youth, landed on April 2, 1513, planted a cross, and took possession of the \"New World\" in the name of the King of Spain. (State Archives of Florida)",
"The entrance and pavilion to the Fountain of Youth, 1921. (State Archives of Florida)",

"The Ponce de Leon Lodge and Country Club in St. Augustine, 1960s. A 300 acre tropical resort offers golf, tennis, world's largest cloverleaf pool. Perfect for honeymooners, vacations, group business meetings. (State Archives of Florida)",

"Photographed is the landing of the \"Spanish Caravel\" carrying Ponce de Leon and escorts for the celebration of the landing of Ponce de Leon in April 1513. Saint Augustine, 1929. (State Archives of Florida/Rahner)",
"A woman standing at the entrance to the Fountain of Youth in the early 1900s. (State Archives of Florida)",

Caption: "Some of Daytona Beach's homeless people are so exhausted by life on the streets that they hope to get a bed at First Step Shelter when it opens late this year or early next year. Construction on the 15,000-square-foot shelter building began two weeks ago. [David Tucker/News-Journal]",

"As miserable as life on the streets can be, a good portion of Daytona Beach's homeless people say they won't use First Step Shelter when it opens at the end of this year or early next year. Some have said that because they mistakenly think they'll only be able to sleep there at night and will be booted back outside every morning. Others just don't like the remote location on the city's western edge. One of those who say they'll never go to the shelter is Tom Jenkins, the man pictured. [News-Journal/David Tucker]",

"Construction of the First Step Shelter building began two weeks ago. The one-story, 15,000-square-foot building will have 100 beds for homeless men and women. The facility on U.S. 92 about five miles west of Interstate 95 is slated to open at the end of this year. [News-Journal/David Tucker]",

"Four shark bites occurred in 2018 in Volusia County, once again making the county the world leader. But shark bites in the Southeast dropped significantly, and researchers believe that's because of a drop in blacktip sharks. Blacktip sharks like this one are suspected to being the leading cause of shark bites off the Southeastern coast of the United States. [Provided by Florida Atlantic University]",

Caption: "Scott Spradley, a Flagler Beach attorney and photographer, shot this photo of a blacktip shark at 7 a.m. on Thursday morning on Flagler Beach. þÄúI knew the bait pods had been out there and I had my eye on the water,þÄù Spradley said. þÄúAll of a sudden, the bait pods started exploding and I started focusing to see if I could catch something like that and bingo, there it was.þÄù",
"Alex Amoroso, Lake Mary, caught this 5-foot-6 long blacktip shark fishing in Daytona Beach. The shark weighed about 150 pounds.",

"Blacktip sharks, Carcharhinus limbatus, commonly cruise the surf zone of Florida's Atlantic coast in pursuit of fish. Gavin Naylor, a shark researcher at the University of Florida, said bites occur when the sharks are catching bait fish and see hands and feet splashing in the water. \"Occasionally their quick decisions are mistakes,\" Naylor said. Illustration by Lindsay Gutteridge, provided by the International Shark Attack File at the University of Florida.",

"Great white sharks, Carcharodon carcharias, were responsible for two bites off Cape Cod, Massachusetts, in 2018. Illustration by Lindsay Gutteridge, provided by the International Shark Attack File at the University of Florida.",

"In this 2017 photo, a blacktip shark is about to be released after being tagged and measured by students and scientists aboard the Florida Institute of Oceanography research vessel Bellows Mote Marine scientists and students from New College and Eckerd College collected data from sharks caught off the coast of Sarasota. The trip gave the students hands-on experience in aspects of catching sharks and collecting data, including setting gear, baiting hooks, handling sharks and releasing them. [Herald-Tribune staff photo / Mike Lang]",

"Blacktip shark: (Carcharhinus limbatus) These are among the larger sharks in North Carolina sounds, reaching lengths of 8 feet, although most measure 6 feet or less. They occur in ocean waters from late spring to late fall and usually move into the sounds during the summer and autumn. Photo by Albert Kok",

Caption: "Josh Jorgensen, Founder and Director of the Blacktip Challenge Shark Fishing Tournament, hauls a blacktip shark ashore on Midtown Beach in Palm Beach Friday afternoon, March 9, 2013. Jorgensen is working with researchers from Nova Southeasten University and St. Mary's Hospital to collect and analyze bacteria from sharks' mouths to help improve the selection of antibiotics used for victims of shark bite victims. They have caught 19 sharks so far, including the two 6-foot backtips they caught Friday. They hope to collect 50 for the project, including some from the Bahamas to get more species. The sharks are migrating through the area this time of the year. \"We heard that they were here, so we came here,\" said Jorgensen, who has been shark fishing for about 10 years. (Lannis Waters/The Palm Beach Post)",
